{
  "doc_id": "15690",
  "text": "Seven of the nine isolates in our study were obtained from apple (Malus ×domestica) and two were from pawpaw (Asimina triloba). Apples with SBFS signs were collected in October of 2006 from orchards located near Lingbao city of Henan Province, and in Mei County of Shaanxi Province, China. Pure isolates were obtained following the protocol of [CITATION_1] . One isolate was selected from each location. After apples with SBFS signs were harvested from orchards in Ardeşen, Rize, Turkey in November of 2008, colonies with subtending apple cuticle were excised, pressed, photographed, and shipped to Iowa State University, Ames, Iowa, U.S.A., and isolation was performed as described elsewhere [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Two isolates from Turkey were included in this study, along with three isolates sampled from apple orchards in Kentucky, Massachusetts and New York, U.S.A., during a 2005 survey (Díaz [CITATION_4] ). Fungal Diversity (2011 The two isolates from pawpaw fruit collected near Iowa City, Iowa, in 2007 were obtained as described for apple [CITATION_5] . Segments of peels exhibiting SBFS signs were pressed between paper towels until dry and preserved; specimens on apple peels were deposited at the Iowa State University Herbarium, Ames, Iowa.",
